@mohammedsafiq In order to analyze a file, infer has to analyze all the procedures called from that file. So if some of these procedures live in different files then they are also analyzed. That doesn't mean that all the procedures in these files were analyzed, only the ones called (transitively!) from the original file.

Hi @mohammedsafiq, Eradicate works pretty much like a type checker, where a value annotated @Nullable is considered as always being potentially null, so local checks for null are required.
In particular, Eradicate does not try to understand the flow of values in a method call, such as `notEmpty(name)`. Another way to look at this: it only considers information at method boundaries, so it will give the same result for any implementation of `notEmpty`, including the one which always returns `true`.

Hi @msridhar.

It is theoretically possible to follow the annotations from the 3rd party libraries. One thing that is not so clear is that different libraries do not necessarily follow the same convention when it comes to `@Nullable`. For example, for analyzed source code, 

is equivalent to:

for Eradicate, meaning that parameter are consider non-nullable by default except when analyzed with `@Nullable` explicitly.

However, your example suggests that we would want to do the opposite assumption for 3rd party libraries when unannotated variables should be considered as `@Nullable` by default except when annotated with `@NonNull`. But this approach would not work for Guava for instance, which uses `@Nullable` more or less as Eradicate expects it. So there should be a way to tell Eradicate, or to detect automatically, which convention is used for each library. 

Or we may want to follow a 3-value logic for libraries and consider no annotation as `unknown` together with `@NonNull` and `@Nullable`

Hi @jeremydubreil yes that's a good point.  My example was contrived; I wanted to keep things simple to make sure I was running the tool correctly.  Probably the right thing to do is to assume usage similar to Guava when annotations from class files are being parsed.  If it's clearly documented, I think that would work well for most cases.  Also, maybe the default should be to behave just as Infer does now (ignoring annotations in class files) to avoid surprises and/or a ton of unwanted false positives.

@sblackshear, it would actually be easy to load the annotations from the 3rd party library. There is already some support for analyzing the dependencies. For example (changing the example a bit to avoid the issue with `@NonNull` mentioned earlier):


and

We can actually have Eradicate report the issue using the undocumented `--dependencies` options:

The reason why we don't use `--dependencies` by default is to avoid duplication of work when using Buck as the same class. e.g. `java.lang.String` could otherwise be analyzed on many different Buck targets.

The new genrule based approach to integrate Infer with Buck could actually allow use to analyze the third party libraries only once (decorating `prebuilt_jar`) and cache the analysis artifacts, which would contain the annotations as well. cc @kageiit

@jeremydubreil That sounds like a great idea. As long as infer knows how to extract the analysis artifacts from the `prebuilt_jar` or `prebuilt_android_aar` decorated infer/eradicate genrules, the performance impact will be minimal and the quality of analysis will be a lot greater. Seems like that is the best approach forward.

Like @jvillard, I think it will be hard to tell without seeing more code, but here's a few ideas off the top of my head:

- Try running infer with `--no-filtering`
- Report on the `proc_name`/ `proc_desc`/`location` of the current procedure rather using `e.proc_desc` and so on. I think all of the checkers we have so far log errors that occur in a function `foo` called from `main` in `main` rather than in `foo` (we have a mechanism for displaying interprocedural traces that will show the path from `main` to `foo`). In principle, reporting the error from anywhere should work, but I haven't tried it.

@cristianoc's advice about disabling the the other checkers is also very important. I forgot to mention this in the documentation, but there's a limitation where we can only register one interprocedural checker at a time (otherwise, they clobber each other's results).

@brotherpaul143 Thanks for your interest in Infer. Perhaps there is some oversight, but as far as we understand Infer does not satisfy the SATE criteria. Infer produces two basic forms of output: 1) specifications of procedures / functions / methods, and 2) issue reports for property violations. Only the inferred specifications are claimed to be sound (subject to some idealistic and optimistic assumptions). Here the notion of sound is that from the logical tradition. In particular, if infer produces {P} f(x) {Q}, then soundness means that execution of f from any state satisfying P does not crash and unless it diverges, the state after f returns satisfies Q. The reports of property violations are produced primarily from failed proofs of such specifications. There is no definition of correctness for these reports, let alone a claim of soundness for them.

@brotherpaul143 it seems that Infer and SATE use two opposite definitions of correct/sound. From your website:

"1. The tool is claimed to be sound."

and

"Sound means every finding is correct. The tool need not produce a finding for every site; that is completeness."

This is simply not the case for Infer: reports made by Infer may not correspond to an actual weakness in the code.

Note that Infer is sound in the logical sense, which seems to correspond to your notion of "completeness": if Infer doesn't report on a procedure, then that procedure has no bugs (as @jberdine said, "subject to some idealistic and optimistic assumptions"). Infer reports a bug when it fails to prove that a procedure has no bugs (and when Infer's internal heuristics suggest that it may correspond to a real issue, otherwise Infer would be too noisy), not when it can prove that a procedure definitely has a bug.

I agree with you, @jvillard   Please note that Ockham uses the term "finding". The use of "finding" allows an additional level of interpretation. As you point out, "if Infer doesn't report on a procedure, then that procedure has no bugs". The _lack_ of a report is a finding for Ockham's purposes. That is, users can absolutely depend on the fact that no bug reportfrom Infer  means that the procedure is bug-free "subject to some idealistic and optimistic assumptions", as @jberdine said.

Infer is welcome to participate in Ockham.

@brotherpaul143, Thanks for bringing this up, and I don't mean to be off-putting.  What you're interpreting as reluctance is more wariness, and the expectation that the reality of how gray questions of soundness and completeness are for tools like Infer undermines the viability of these sorts of exercises.  In particular, Infer uses both sound techniques and heuristics which are neither sound nor complete.  Additionally, Infer uses the classical logical notion of soundness, which seems to correspond more to what you term completeness.  Infer does not do any reasoning that fits what you term "soundness".  The other difficulty is that the logically robust reasoning that Infer does produces specifications that are used internally by Infer, but not directly reported to developers.  Evaluating the correctness of these specifications is nontrivial, since they are hypothetical statements with very involved premisses.

@brotherpaul143 I think a good summary is that Infer comes from sound design principles, makes unsound compromises and heuristics where it makes sense. In particular, Infer tries to maximize the value given to developers, over soundness or completeness concerns.

Now that all the provisos are out of the way, the main question is whether, given these provisos, you think that the results will be useful for SATE V. I guess this is for you to assess.

You're right though: with the heuristics filtering results before they reach the user, Infer is not a candidate for the Ockham criteria track in SATE VI. However, Infer would fit very well in other tracks in SATE VI.

Again, thanks for patiently answering my questions, @jberdine and @jvillard too.

@mishudark The version of `git` might be too old on your system. You'll need to install Reason manually for now I'm afraid. Something like this may work:
1. select the infer-4.02.3 opam switch: `opam switch infer-4.02.3 && eval $(opam config env)`
2. clone the Reason repo locally, checkout its 0.0.1 release, then `opam pin add -k git reason .` inside the repo should install reason from there
3. run `./build-infer.sh` from the infer repo again

Thanks for the detailed question, @wouter89. What you are seeing is because infer doesn't do a global analysis of a class (in this case `NoNullDereference`) to figure out invariants (in this case "`alwaysFalse` is always `false`"). To explain, let me try and go over your tests:
1. Infer analyses `test()` on its own (without looking at the context) and finds that it could dereference `null` if `alwaysFalse` is `true`. Since infer doesn't try to analyse the context of the method, only the method itself, it doesn't know that `alwaysFalse` cannot in fact be `true`. The analysis of `main()` shows no error.
2. Same as 1, except this time it turns out that `alwaysTrue` can indeed be `true` to this report turns out to be legit.
3. Infer analyses `test()` and finds no issue. It stores 2 specifications about `test()`: A) when `alwaysTrue` is `true` then the return value is `null`; B) otherwise it is `"hello"`. Infer then analyses `main()`. At the point where `main()` calls `test()`, the value of `nullDereference.alwaysTrue` is `true`, so infer uses specification A and then finds an error when simulating the execution of `null.trim()`.
4. Similar to 3, except than at the point where `main()` calls `test()` infer selects specification B and doesn't find any error when symbolically executing `"hello".trim()`.
5. Infer analyses `test()` and finds no error because it knows which branch to take in `if (false) ...`.
6. Same as 5 and Infer correctly finds the NPE.

I hope this answers your question. Feel free to open another issue about the general fact that infer doesn't try to find out which fields never change before anaylising the methods in a class.

With Retrolambda in the mix, the Android build process is something like:
- Run `javac` over your source files to produce Java 8 bytecode.
- Retrolambda transforms the bytecode to be Java 6/7 compatible.
- `dx` transforms the transformed bytecode into a `.dex` file.

I believe that Infer relies on the `javac` output from the gradle build process (please correct me if I'm mistaken--certainly no expert here), so maybe the issue is that it's using the pre-transformed bytecode.

(I'll try to put together a minimal example.)

Two quick asides, though:
1. It's unclear to me if this is worth fixing right now, since I imagine that a lot will have to change with the introduction of [Jack](http://developer.android.com/preview/j8-jack.html) (already available in the N developer preview), which will make some Java 8 language features standard in Android (backwards compatible to Gingerbread) and will remove the `javac` step from the Android build process.
2. Not relevant to this particular issue, but... it's interesting to me that Infer operates on bytecode, yet it ties in so well with annotations, which (I believe?) are stripped out by the time you get to bytecode (again, please correct me if I'm wrong). Are there any resources around for learning more about how that works?

Thanks for the detailed update @crm416. Skipping Java 8 files and not crashing is the expected behaviour, there's a fix in 0.8.0 to reintroduce it.

For infer to be able to analyse code compiled with retrolambda, one of these two things needs to happen:
1. Java 8 support is added to Infer (#314)
2. Support for starting from the bytecode instead of from the Java source is added to Infer (#308)

1 is planned, and there's nothing stopping 2 in principle, since our Java frontend already starts from Java bytecode (only some rearchitecturing is needed to be able to not start from the sources).

I'm closing this issue since it's been resolved. Use the other two issues to track progress on the larger issue of dealing with Java8 bytecode.
Thanks for looking into this, @kstreee! We'll be pushing further improvements to that part of the code soon as well.

You probably don't need to use dest-$CC to compile infer and the facebook-clang-plugins. (The error you get is because your dest-$CC is indeed too old)

The Makefile you pasted does not seem to contain any build rules, it just calls other Makefiles. To be able to help, it would be great to see an example invocation of the compiler as called by your Makefiles.

One possibility for your issue is if your Makefile gives several source files to $CC at once. Infer cannot deal with this. For instance, `infer -- gcc -c a.c b.c` does not work. Instead, one should use `infer -- gcc -c a.c && infer -- gcc -c b.c`. I realise now that we seem to have forgotten to document this!

Hi @denizt. Thanks for reporting this. Yes, Infer does not currently analyses the standard libraries. It only analyses what gets compiled and does not know what `TextUtils.isEmpty` does in this case. It especially does not know that `TextUtils.isEmpty(states)` returns `true` when `statues == null`. 

I am keeping this task opened for now as we may start to analyse some part of the standard library in the future, which could fix this false positive.

As @jvillard said, `NSUserDefaults+App.h` doesn't look like a system header, so I'd proceed as he suggested, by passing to Clang the path where this file lives, using the `-I` argument.

More in general, when `xcodebuild` builds each file of your codebase, it passes to Clang more arguments than just the source filename, and among those there's the `-isysroot` one, which tells Clang where your SDK lives.
For example, your iPhoneSimulator SDK should be located in:



try passing `-isysroot <SDK_PATH>` to your Clang command.

Workaround
--- 

### Generate a json compilation database
If you add the [following parameter](http://oclint-docs.readthedocs.io/en/stable/guide/xctool.html#running-xctool-with-json-compilation-database-reporter) to 
* `xctool`: `-reporter json-compilation-database:compile_commands.json` 
* `xcpretty`:  `-r json-compilation-database -o compile_commands.json`

#### This'll enable you to use one of the following commands: 
Depending on how you generate this file you use one of the following options:
*  `xcpretty` and `xctool`: `--clang-compilation-db-files-escaped` 
    * reason: the files in the json are escaped : 'file\\ with\\ spaces'
* `cmake`: `--clang-compilation-db-files`

Granted, it'd be a 2 step process, but it'll work 👍 

**NB** Commonly, the build output will be stored in a file called 'xcodebuild.log'. If you need a different reporter for e.g. your test, you can still do that, generate the `compile_commands.json` using that log file, and launch infer using that generated `compile_commands.json`

Concretely:
1. `xctool.sh --<whatever parameters you need> -reporter json-compilation-database:compile_commands.json` or `xcodebuild --<whatever parameters> | tee xcodebuild.log | xcpretty -r junit -o junit.xml` as usual
2. `cat xcodebuild.log | xcpretty -r json-compilation-database -o compile_commands.json &> /dev/null`
    * the last part pipes the output  to `/dev/null`, as otherwise it'd be displayed on screen again, convoluting your build log.
3. `infer --skip-analysis-in-path Pods --clang-compilation-db-files-escaped compile_commands.json`

Having support for `@SuppressWarnings` is very tricky because the default `@SuppressWarnings` annotation only source retention only, and Infer runs on bytecode. Hi @mohammedsafiq, Eradicate works pretty much like a type checker, where a value annotated @Nullable is considered as always being potentially null, so local checks for null are required.
In particular, Eradicate does not try to understand the flow of values in a method call, such as `notEmpty(name)`. Another way to look at this: it only considers information at method boundaries, so it will give the same result for any implementation of `notEmpty`, including the one which always returns `true`.

Are `filename1` and `filename2` relative paths to the files from the project root? If you are running Eradicate from `myproject/` and `filename1` is at `myproject/src/com/my/project/filename1`, .inferconfig would expect `src/com/my/project/filename` in `eradicate_blacklist`.

In addition, note that the blacklist does not actually stop Eradicate from running on those files altogether; it just stops Eradicate from reporting any errors on those files. If there are other files that call `@Nullable` methods from `filename1` (directly, or transitively), those errors will still be reported.

Hi @msridhar.

It is theoretically possible to follow the annotations from the 3rd party libraries. One thing that is not so clear is that different libraries do not necessarily follow the same convention when it comes to `@Nullable`. For example, for analyzed source code, 

is equivalent to:

for Eradicate, meaning that parameter are consider non-nullable by default except when analyzed with `@Nullable` explicitly.

However, your example suggests that we would want to do the opposite assumption for 3rd party libraries when unannotated variables should be considered as `@Nullable` by default except when annotated with `@NonNull`. But this approach would not work for Guava for instance, which uses `@Nullable` more or less as Eradicate expects it. So there should be a way to tell Eradicate, or to detect automatically, which convention is used for each library. 

Or we may want to follow a 3-value logic for libraries and consider no annotation as `unknown` together with `@NonNull` and `@Nullable`

Hi Michael,
  We don't currently have any special support for JUnit annotations like `@Test`, but we could add support if there is a need.

In general, I'm skeptical of the utility of statically analyzing small pieces of test code like your example (since one can always just run the code and let JUnit check if the right thing happens). But I'm intrigued by the possibility of using JUnit assertions to specify statically checkable contracts in non-test code. Let me me know if you are interested in that use case/have examples and we can try to throw some support together.

A tad unrelated direction is to use infer's blacklisting options to avoid analysing or reporting on these files, unless tests and regular source codes are mixed together.

For instance: `--infer-blacklist-files-containing "@Test("` or `--infer-blacklist-files-containing "import org.junit.Test;"`. These options (like all options) can also go into a .inferconfig file.

@jvillard

I think that there might be some confusion here about what information `icfg.dot` is presenting.  The `icfg.dot` files contain the static control-flow graph, which is determined by the source code and control-flow paths that might be impossible are not removed.

From the comments, with the mention of e.g. "which variable is symbolic", it seems that @zzy assumes that infer operates in a way similar to King-style symbolic execution.  I don't think that trying to understand what infer does in these terms is useful, since what it actually does is very different.  A better starting point is probably http://dl.acm.org/citation.cfm?doid=2049697.2049700.

Strictly speaking, it's true that the code will not generate an NPE. That said, the choice Infer makes is to report anyway. If a project deliberately catches `NullPointerException`, Infer will produce a lot of unintended reports. For such projects (if they exist), a different message would help.

I suspect that it would be hard to implement that behaviour in infer: if `foo()` dereferences null, then infer will want to report on `foo()`. But maybe `foo()` is only called from inside `bar()`, which catches `Exception` or `NullPointerException`. Currently, infer has no way to know every context in which `foo()` is called prior to analysing `foo()`, so it would be hard to avoid reporting on `foo()`.

That said, as @martinoluca was saying in #422, such code patterns are dubious at best anyway.

It would be great to support them in general as they give a lot of contextual information about how a method handles inputs. The example in there about a method that only returns `null` if the input parameter is `null` is a great example. Being able to express other conditions in that format would be great too. Being able to mark methods as throwing on certain conditions would be immense as well.

Looking at the page again, I think it would be great to support `@ParametersAreNonnullByDefault` annotation as well, as it also looks pretty useful.

Can you provide a full minimal example that reproduces your issue? Shooting from the hip, you could add a `@Nullable` annotation to the return of your getter method so that Infer assumes it can return null.

More (speculative) details: When Infer doesn't know about a function for whatever reason (no implementation available, or Infer failed to analyse it), Infer will treat that function "angelically" and assume that eg it never returns null. This is done to prevent being too noisy. This may or may not be what's happening in your case, we'd need to see some code to know for sure.

@chen881129 I guess you're using eradicate mode with `-a eradicate`.
Is the return type of `getClassid()` annotated `@Nullable`?

@cristianoc . Yeah, I used eradicate mode.
There is no error about `getClassid() may return null but it is not annotated with @Nullable` in the bug.txt.

@chen881129 you should annotate `getClassid()` in your source code, e.g.
`@Nullable String getClassid() { ... }`

@chen881129,
  Is your copy of the code read-only, or is it possible to change it locally just for testing? Or can you suggest that someone else add the `@Nullable` annotation? This seems like it would be the simplest solution.

It would be quite difficult to change Eradicate to treat all values as potentially nullable, but it should be fairly easy to modify Infer to do this. If you change the code [here](https://github.com/facebook/infer/blob/master/infer/src/backend/rearrange.ml#L1144) to 



and delete lines 1145-1184, Infer should warn on ever deref unless it can prove the value being dereferenced is non-null.

Hi @Tony-Mao, there is a rudimentary array bounds analysis in Infer, but the reports are filtered out by default as this feature is not supported at the moment and performs quite poorly. You can remove error filtering by running with the `--no-filtering` option (see `infer --help`).

We're working on improving the array bounds analysis.

Unfortunately, it is hard to tell what is happening without more context about the definition of `Controler`. If I understood correctly, the constructor is of the form: 

  `Controller(..., @Nullable Object obj) { ...}`

where `obj` is not being dereference without a check for `null` inside the body of `Controler`. If that was the case, then the NPE would be reported in the body of `Controler`, not when calling the constructor with `null` somewhere else.

@hzsweers apologies for the code... that group is used to define annotations that have the property `ia_is_inject`, which suppresses `FIELD_NOT_NULLABLE`.
In addition `@InjectView` has the property `ia_is_inject_view`, which suppresses `FIELD_NOT_NULLABLE`.
So if you want both, you should modify the code for `ia_is_inject_view`.

Those properties should definitely be renamed to something less confusing: what they suppress.

Basically:

**Butter Knife 6** and before: `@InjectView` would cause a runtime exception if the view was null after binding. Could optionally add `@Optional` if you wanted to allow for nulls. Behavior applies to fields and methods.



**Butter Knife 7**: `@Bind` was the same as `@InjectView` functionally, but `@Optional` was removed in favor of reusing `@Nullable` so the IDE would lint it. Same idea though. Behavior applies to fields and methods.



**Butter Knife 8+**: Unreleased, but behavior will be the same with fields. For methods however, `@Optional` was re-added because it was strange to require `@Nullable` for methods since many had `void` return types. Note that it's only allowed on methods however, fields must still use `@Nullable`



---

All in all: I think `bind` should be included as well then since its behavior is functionally the same and this only applies to fields. The problem arises in the situation where you have both `@Nullable` and `@Bind` annotations on a field, which I'm not sure if infer is aware and can ensure that `@Nullable` overrules.

CONFIG_SHELL := $(shell if [ -x "$$BASH" ]; then echo $$BASH; \

      else echo sh; fi ; fi)
CENV := $(shell if [ `uname` = "Linux" ]; then echo linux; else echo cygwin; fi)

top_srcdir := $(shell pwd)

all: do-it-all

OUTPUT_DIR := $(top_srcdir)/build

ADD_CFLAGS  =

ifeq ($(CONFIG_GCOV),y)
GCOV_FLAGS := -fprofile-arcs -ftest-coverage
endif

export MAKEFLAGS += $(JOB_SLOTS)
export MAKEFILES += ${KCONFIG}

export CONFIG_SHELL OUTPUT_DIR GCOV_FLAGS ADD_CFLAGS
export top_srcdir  

unexport rootdir-y

include $(KCONFIG)

include $(top_srcdir)/Rules.mk

PKG := mng

VERSION := 1.0.0

src_type := svn

rootdir-y := 
rootdir-$(CONFIG_xxx1) += tech_support
rootdir-$(CONFIG_xxx2) += syslog

.PHONY: header
header:
    ln -s -f ${ROOTFS_BUILD}/$(PKG)/cli/common/ ${ROOTFS_BUILD}/$(PKG)/cli/server/common

.PHONY: do-it-all
do-it-all: build 

.PHONY: build
build: $(patsubst %, _dir_%, $(rootdir-y))
$(patsubst %, _dir_%, $(rootdir-y)): 
    $(MAKE) CFLAGS="$(CFLAGS)" -C $(top_srcdir)/$(patsubst _dir_%,%, $@) _PDIR="$(OUTPUT_DIR)/$(patsubst _dir_%,%, $@)"
    @echo "Compiled OK! find output in $(OUTPUT_DIR)/$(patsubst _dir_%,%, $@)"
    @echo

.PHONY: install
install:
    n=`ls $(install_root)/ | wc -l`; \
    if [ $$n -gt 0 ] ; then \
        cp -a -rf $(install_root)/\* ${IMAGES}; fi

.PHONY: rpmpkg
rpmpkg:
    $(RPMPKG) $(install_rootfs_dir) $(PKG).spec $(src_type)

.PHONY: gcov-docs
gcov-docs:
    @-for dir in $(rootdir-y) ; do \
    lcov -c -b $$dir -d $$dir -o $$dir.info; \
    genhtml -o $(GCOV_DOCS)/$(PKG)-$(VERSION)/$$dir $$dir.info --title $$dir; done

.PHONY: version
version:
    @echo ${VERSION}

.PHONY:gcov-cp-gcda
gcov-cp-gcda:
    @tar zxf gcov_*.tar.gz -C $(PKG)

.PHONY: clean
clean:
    @-for dir in $(rootdir-y) ; do \
    $(MAKE) -C $$dir clean ; done
    @rm -rf $(shell find -name "_.gcda" && find -name "_.gcno" && find -name "report" && find -name "_.info" && find -name "_.o")
    @rm -rf $(install_root)
    @rm -rf $(OUTPUT_DIR)

PKG := mng

.PHONY: header

.PHONY: do-it-all
do-it-all: build 

.PHONY: build
build: $(patsubst %, _dir_%, $(rootdir-y))
$(patsubst %, _dir_%, $(rootdir-y)): 
    $(MAKE) CFLAGS="$(CFLAGS)" -C $(top_srcdir)/$(patsubst _dir_%,%, $@) _PDIR="$(OUTPUT_DIR)/$(patsubst _dir_%,%, $@)"
    @echo "Compiled OK! find output in $(OUTPUT_DIR)/$(patsubst _dir_%,%, $@)"
    @echo

.PHONY: install
install:
    n=`ls $(install_root)/ | wc -l`; \
    if [ $$n -gt 0 ] ; then \
        cp -a -rf $(install_root)/\* ${IMAGES}; fi

    lcov -c -b $$dir -d $$dir -o $$dir.info; \

    @echo ${VERSION}

    @tar zxf gcov_*.tar.gz -C $(PKG)

Yes, you can create a JSON file named `.inferconfig` which should be in the directory where Infer is run. This allow to enable or disable the analysis at the level of files or directories. For example:



will have the effect of enabling Infer on all the files in the `src/` sub-directory unless they are under `src/third-party` or they contain the string `@DISABLE_INFER`.

@denizt Yes, Infer now supports the java.lang `@SuppressWarnings` [annotation](http://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/lang/SuppressWarnings.html). I am getting this RETAIN_CYCLE (type names and instance variables renamed to show weak/strong):

Retain cycle involving the following objects:  (1) an object of class TYPE_A  retaining another object via instance variable _varForWeakPropertyInA,  (2) an object of class TYPE_B  retaining another object via instance variable _varForStrongPropertyinB,  (3) an object of class TYPE_C  retaining another object via instance variable _varForWeakPropertyInC,   

So, in this cycle, two of the instance variables are for weak properties.  One thing that might be causing the problem is that the properties are declared this way in the `@interface` in the .h

`@property (nonatomic, readonly, weak) T *varForWeakPropertyInC;`

And, then in an anonymous category in the .m, it is changed like this:

`@property (nonatomic, weak) T *varForWeakPropertyInC;`

We do this to allow the class to write to its own property, but only expose a readonly property to other classes.  It's weak in both cases for both variables (I checked).

The actual code is hard to include with all of its context, but I can try to find a minimal example if you think weak properties work properly.  I can say that I am doing this on a very large codebase with tons of `weak` and block usage and this was the only RETAIN_CYCLE it found in the entire app (so I think it might be particular to this code).

Thank you @markddaa for reporting the entire error message, the cause of your issue is this:
`error: use of '@import' when modules are disabled`
It is a known issue and there's a task open for that here https://github.com/facebook/infer/issues/2

Have a look in the issues, there is already a similar report. We are working on it.
